            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mark Schmidt\u2019s life is measured in the grain of wood and the satisfying ache in his hands. He grew up in the sprawling suburbs of Sacramento, the son of a pragmatic German-American engineer who taught him the value of a well-made joint but saw little use for art. This practical foundation, however, couldn\u2019t suppress Mark\u2019s creative drive. He rebelled quietly, sketching designs in the margins of his math homework and finding solace in his high school woodshop.\n\nAgainst his father\u2019s advice, he moved to San Francisco in the late 90s to pursue a Bachelor of Fine Arts at SF State. The city\u2019s vibrant, unconventional energy was a revelation. He fell in love with sculpture but realized he craved a connection between art and utility. This fusion led him to custom furniture making, a path he began by apprenticing in a small Potrero Hill workshop after graduation.\n\nThe 2008 financial crisis was his turning point. Laid off from the workshop, Mark cashed in his meager savings, leased a raw, affordable industrial space in the still-gritty Dogpatch neighborhood, and founded \"Schmidt Furnishings.\" The early years were lean, fueled by ramen and sheer will, and the strain contributed to the amicable end of his first marriage. Yet, he slowly built a reputation for his minimalist, exquisitely crafted pieces.\n\nToday, Mark\u2019s life is rooted in his neighborhood. He lives in a small Edwardian flat and begins each day with a 1.8-mile bicycle ride down the hill to his workshop, a commute that clears his head. His income of $115,000 affords him a comfortable, unpretentious life. He is in a stable, loving relationship with a graphic designer who understands the rhythm of a creative life. Mark\u2019s connection to San Francisco is tactile; he feels it in the fog rolling over the hills and the community of makers who, like him, have held on. His dream isn\u2019t expansion but mastery. He hopes to one day take on a dedicated apprentice, passing on the craft and ensuring that in a city obsessed with the ephemeral, some things are still built to last."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers his father visiting his high school woodshop, expecting to see a simple, sturdy birdhouse. Instead, Mark showed him a small, sculpted box joined with immaculate, hand-cut dovetails. His father ran a thumb over the interlocking grain, silent for a long moment before grunting, \u201cPrecise. Unnecessary, but precise.\u201d In that single-word compliment, Mark didn\u2019t find the approval he craved, but the fuel for his quiet rebellion. It was the first time he knew his precision could be used for beauty, not just function. This happened his junior year, around 1995.\n\n2.\nHe can still feel the electric shock of his first walk through Clarion Alley, just weeks after moving to the city in 1998. The sheer, explosive creativity\u2014vibrant murals screaming from every surface\u2014was overwhelming. It wasn't in a gallery; it was alive, public, and part of the city's skin. He realized then that art didn't have to be contained. It could be functional, lived-in, and woven into the very fabric of daily life. That walk cemented his desire to create things that people would touch and use every day.\n\n3.\nThe day he got the keys to the Dogpatch workshop in 2008 remains his defining moment of terror and hope. He stood alone in the vast, dusty space, the scent of cold concrete and old grease filling his lungs. His savings account was decimated. For a moment, his father\u2019s pragmatism screamed at him. But then, a profound sense of ownership washed over him. This empty space was his. That echo of his first footsteps on the concrete floor was the sound of betting everything on himself, forging a resilience he never knew he had.\n\n4.\nHe recalls delivering his first major commission around 2011: a large dining table made of reclaimed Monterey cypress. The client, a woman in the Sunset, touched the tabletop almost reverently and started crying softly. She said she could already picture generations of her family gathered around it. Seeing his work, his sweat and artistry, become the instant heart of a home was a visceral validation. It quieted the years of doubt and ramen noodles, proving his craft had a soul that resonated with others.\n\n5.\nJust last spring, riding his bike down the 22nd Street hill, he saw the fog swallowing the tops of the Potrero hills. A deep, quiet contentment settled in his chest. He wasn't rushing or striving for more; he was simply moving through a city he knew intimately, on his way to a workshop he built, to a life he\u2019d shaped with his own hands. Waiting for him at the end of the day was a partner who understood. It wasn\u2019t a dramatic epiphany, but a profound, peaceful realization of arrival."
